{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure boundary is real filesystem watch behavior (recursive subscription and path event delivery), not just local parsing logic. A mocked watcher can hide real recursive-watch misconfiguration or OS-specific event delivery gaps for nested paths (REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE).","test_description":"Start the daemon against a real temp directory tree, create `root/subdir/new.txt`, and assert the transformed output appears in the output directory. Verify this with the daemon running continuously (no restart) and real OS file events.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This behavior is centered on deterministic dedup window/path logic in one component; no real OS/network/subprocess is required. Higher levels were considered, but rejected because the behavior text focuses on \"deduplication logic\" and \"same file path within a configurable time window,\" which can be validated with a fake clock and in-memory state.","test_description":"Call the dedup component twice with the same canonical path inside the configured window using a controlled clock; assert first request is accepted and second is discarded, then accepted again after the window expires.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Integration/System are unnecessary unless the behavior also required real watcher event semantics or queue handoff races, which are not stated here.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.72,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The behavior explicitly depends on OS-emitted duplicate filesystem events. This is a real infrastructure boundary; in-process fakes commonly miss actual event burst patterns, so mocking can mask failures (REAL-INFRA, MOCK-HIDE).","test_description":"Run the daemon with a real watched directory, perform a single write operation known to generate multiple events (e.g., write/rename pattern), and assert exactly one pipeline execution/output artifact for that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This failure appears at the OS watcher boundary (directory inode invalidation/recreation and reattachment). Module-only tests cannot faithfully reproduce directory removal/recreate watch semantics (REAL-INFRA, MOCK-HIDE).","test_description":"Start daemon watching a real directory, remove that directory, recreate it at the same path, then add a new file and assert it is processed without restarting the daemon process.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.92,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The core failure is cross-module handoff/order/state propagation (watch intake -> queueing -> timestamp-based ordering), matching the integration boundary. Rejected higher level System: behavior text requires ordering by timestamps, but does not require validating OS-specific watcher quirks or network/subprocess effects. This follows the integration brake and the dual-quote gate: explicit orchestration/order behavior across modules.","test_description":"Wire watcher-event ingestion, metadata lookup abstraction, and processing queue in-process. Inject near-simultaneous arrival requests with controlled creation timestamps and assert processing order follows timestamps, not event arrival order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"If implementation derives creation time only from real filesystem APIs with OS-dependent semantics, add a System test as a supplement; minimum boundary here is module orchestration.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is fundamentally about real filesystem timing/write-completion behavior and real watcher timing, which in-process mocks often simplify away. The exact failure appears under real OS I/O timing (REAL-INFRA, MOCK-HIDE).","test_description":"With daemon running, begin a slow/streamed write to a file in the watched directory, emit/observe arrival event naturally, verify processing does not start until write completes, then confirm single successful transformed output.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
